# React Native & Expo Best Practices

## Tech Stack
- **Framework**: Expo (Managed Workflow)
- **Language**: TypeScript
- **Package Manager**: Bun
- **Styling**: NativeWind (Tailwind CSS)
- **Navigation**: Expo Router (preferred) or React Navigation

## General Guidelines
- **Modern Syntax**: Always use modern JavaScript/TypeScript features (e.g., `async/await`, arrow functions, destructuring).
- **Functional Components**: Use functional components with Hooks. Avoid class components.
- **Strict Types**: Use strict TypeScript types. Avoid `any` where possible.

## Styling (NativeWind/Tailwind)
- Use `className` prop for styling components (NativeWind).
- For conditional styles, use libraries like `clsx` or `tailwind-merge` if available, or template literals.
- Ensure `global.css` is imported in the root component.

## React Native vs. React Web
- **Primitives**: Use `<View>`, `<Text>`, `<Image>`, `<TouchableOpacity>` (or `<Pressable>`) instead of `<div>`, `<span>`, `<img>`, `<button>`.
- **Text Handling**: All text must be wrapped in `<Text>` components.
- **Flexbox**: Flexbox is the default layout model and defaults to `flexDirection: 'column'` (unlike `row` in web).
- **Platform Specifics**: Handle platform differences using `Platform.OS` or platform-specific file extensions (`.ios.tsx`, `.android.tsx`).

## Documentation & Resources
- Follow best practices from:
  - [React Native Docs](https://reactnative.dev/docs)
  - [React Docs](https://react.dev)
  - [Expo Docs](https://docs.expo.dev)

## Workflow
- When explaining new concepts, explicitly highlight differences from React Web (DOM vs Native, Styling, etc.).
- Use `bun` for all package management commands (`bun install`, `bun add`).
